title: express.listen() should return http.Server
body:
In express 3.x, express no longer inherits from http.Server.  Instead, express.listen() should return an http.Server object that you can use to get the current port or stop the express server, for example.

I found the node definitions were also incorrect.  The .listen() and .close() methods should return a Server object, and the http.Server should have an address() definition.

This patch makes the appropriate updates to both the node and express definitions.

title: Limited refactor of node.d.ts and express.d.ts
body:
This refactor allows express requests and responses to have their type
declarations reopened/extended. This requires these types to reside in
internal modules, so they have been moved to one called `Express` in
express.d.ts.

`Express.Response` extends node's `"http".ServerResponse`, but internal
modules cannot access types declared within external modules, so the
types in `"http"` have been moved to an internal module called `NodeJs.Http`
in node.d.ts.

In a similar way, the `"http"` declarations depend on the `"net"` module's
`Socket` interface, so that has also been moved into an internal module
called `NodeJs.Net` in node.d.ts.

This PR has zero impact on existing external module declarations, they have all the same type declarations identically as before. But now several types are additionally available ambiently, eg `NodeJs.Net.Socket`, `NodeJs.Http.Server`, `Express.Request`, `Express.Response`, `Express.Application`.

title: Reorder select2 overloads from most specific to least specific so overlo...
body:
...ad resolution behaves as expected.

Discovered while investigating https://typescript.codeplex.com/workitem/2182. When TypeScript detects ambiguous overloads it resolves to the first candidate signature in the type definition, so it is important to author overloads in order of most specific to least specific. In particular, string overloads must come after specialized signatures or else the specialized signatures will never be called. In addition, the Select2Options type has 0 required parameters, which means it is an extremely permissive type and should be listed last or else nearly any single parameter overload will resolve to the overload which takes a Select2Options argument if it is listed first. Concrete examples of the behavior prior to this fix:

``` JavaScript
var r1 = $(null).select2('data'); // specialized signature returned JQuery, should be 'any'
var r2 = $(null).select2('destroy'); // specialized signature returned JQuery, should be 'void'
var r3 = $(null).select2('hmm'); // string signature returned JQuery, should be 'any'
var r4 = $(null).select2({ tags: null }); // Select2Options signature returns JQuery
var r5 = $(null).select2({ id: 1, text: 'hello' }); // IdTextPair signature returns JQuery
```

My first pull request so hopefully I did this correctly :)
